Let's create a simple example of a form that accepts and saves user-inputted text. We'll use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript to create a form that collects user input and stores it in a local storage.

**Example: Simple Text Form**

**HTML:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Simple Text Form</title>
  <style>
    /* Add some basic styling to our form */
    form {
      width: 50%;
      margin: 40px auto;
      padding: 20px;
      border: 1px solid #ccc;
      border-radius: 10px;
      box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
    }
    label {
      display: block;
      margin-bottom: 10px;
    }
    input[type="text"] {
      width: 100%;
      height: 40px;
      padding: 10px;
      border: 1px solid #ccc;
    }
    button[type="submit"] {
      width: 100%;
      height: 40px;
      background-color: #4CAF50;
      color: #fff;
      padding: 10px;
      border: none;
      border-radius: 5px;
      cursor: pointer;
    }
    button[type="submit"]:hover {
      background-color: #3e8e41;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Simple Text Form</h1>
  <form id="text-form">
    <label for="text-input">Enter your text:</label>
    <input type="text" id="text-input" name="text-input">
    <button type="submit">Submit</button>
  </form>
  <div id="output"></div>

  <script>
    // Get the form and output elements
    const form = document.getElementById('text-form');
    const output = document.getElementById('output');

    // Add an event listener to the form's submit event
    form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
      e.preventDefault();

      // Get the user's input
      const userInput = document.getElementById('text-input').value;

      // Store the user's input in local storage
      localStorage.setItem('userInput', userInput);

      // Display the user's input in the output element
      output.innerHTML = `You entered: ${userInput}`;
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```
**How it works:**

1. The form is created using HTML, with a text input field and a submit button.
2. When the user submits the form, the JavaScript code gets the user's input and stores it in local storage using the `localStorage.setItem()` method.
3. The code then displays the user's input in the output element using the `innerHTML` property.

**What students can learn from this example:**

1. How to create a simple form using HTML and CSS.
2. How to add event listeners to form elements using JavaScript.
3. How to store user input in local storage using the `localStorage` API.
4. How to display user input in a web page using JavaScript.

This example demonstrates a simple yet effective way to create a form that accepts and saves user-inputted text. By following this example, students can see how the theoretical lessons they've learned connect to real-world application.

